99a530e4-88e8-4e33-988d-c69264ef1f3c	2bcefae4-ae74-41a5-9ae5-480486230bab	Highly creative and cute little restaurant.\nWe had an unexpectedly good time - almost fine dining vibes for some of the dishes.\n\nWe had the ceviche (experimental but great), the lake tiradito (amazing!!), and lemon cloud (super - think lemon cest meets crême brûlée).\n\nClearly a hidden jem in the sacred valley.	Delilah c.	5
b7cd822d-39ad-48d6-902c-03e7e5eb442f	2bcefae4-ae74-41a5-9ae5-480486230bab	In retrospect, we should have paid attention to the little voice in our heads telling us to turn around and leave right after we had entered. The restaurant had a dark and dingy vibe, smelled a bit dank and was completely empty. The prices were well over the top (higher even than a classy place in Cusco) so we ordered the ceviche and trout main (which turned out to be very similar in nature). The fusion effort didn’t quite fly, but the fish was ample and pretty good, aside from the price gauging. The nail in the coffin for this place was the service. The chef/waiter/owner? was on speaker phone for most of our meal, so we had to listen to a combination of the shmaltzy music and his conversation as our dining backdrop. When we finished, he cleared the table and we indicated that we were complete. Instead of bringing the bill, he proceeded to go outside and start another phone conversation in the road. We waited a while, went to the bathroom etc and eventually I had to go out in the road and wave a credit card in his face to get his attention so we could pay and get out of there. He clearly knew he was out of line as he apologized, but the bad taste was already in our mouths. As it was, we spent over 100 soles to have our least favorite dining experience in the Valley. For a restaurant advertising and charging for a fabulous vibe, this is a fail.	June Adjii	3
1aad9ec9-354f-476f-8768-22170a3f9d86	2bcefae4-ae74-41a5-9ae5-480486230bab	There are moments in life when you realize you’ve stumbled into something rare.\nNot hyped.\nNot branded to death.\nNot trying to impress anyone.\n\nJust quietly… devastatingly good.\n\nIntimo in Pisac is one of those places.\n\nI still don’t understand how a restaurant of this caliber exists in such a small Andean town, tucked away in the Sacred Valley like a secret meant only for those paying attention. This is not “good for Pisac.” This is not “surprisingly good.” This is world-class cuisine, full stop.\n\nChef Alex is a true master of the culinary arts.\n\nNot a technician chasing trends.\nNot a performer plating ego.\nA craftsman.\nA listener.\nSomeone who understands food the way musicians understand silence.\n\nEvery dish that came out of that kitchen carried intention. Balance. Restraint. Confidence. The kind of confidence that doesn’t need explanation. Gourmet, Michelin-level compositions that would hold their own in Paris, Tokyo, or New York… yet somehow feel grounded, warm, and deeply human.\n\nAnd the service…\n\nA genuine smile.\nA warm heart.\nPresence.\n\nYou’re not being “served.”\nYou’re being welcomed.\n\nWhat made the experience even more remarkable was the care. My girlfriend and I are currently in ketosis, eating a low-carb, zero-sugar diet.\n\nNo “we can try.”\nChef Alex simply adjusted.\nQuietly. Masterfully.\nModifying dishes with elegance and respect for the integrity of the cuisine.\n\nThe result was extraordinary.\n\nFlavors were rich and clean.\nTextures thoughtful.\nPresentation absolutely world-class.\n\nNothing felt like a compromise.\nNothing felt “diet.”\n\nIt felt like a private tasting menu designed just for us.\n\nThis place is a bit hidden.\nReservations are required.\nAnd that’s exactly how it should be.\n\nIntimo isn’t trying to be found by everyone. It’s a reward for those who wander a little deeper… who trust instinct over Google reviews… who understand that the best meals of your life rarely announce themselves.\n\nThis is not just a great restaurant.\n\nThis is a true culinary gem in the Sacred Valley.\nA destination.\nA memory that will follow you long after you leave Peru.\n\nIf you care about food…\nIf you care about craft…\nIf you care about soul…\n\nYou go to Intimo.\n\nNo question.	Eric Graham	5
