829fd72b-9a07-4644-a5a1-dc1411f5dbeb	a079c2fa-7503-4c97-80dd-c11337187217	I stayed at Hotel Samanapaq in the Sacred Valley as part of a group of eight adults (ages 40–50) and unfortunately had a very poor experience.\n\nThe property is in significant disrepair and should not be marketed as a hotel in its current condition. The mattresses were extremely thin (with no box spring), resulting in back pain and a sleepless night for several of us. Portable heaters were provided but were not sufficient to properly warm the rooms.\n\nOne guest experienced a water leak in her room and discovered visible mold on the ceiling. She woke up with congestion and allergy-type symptoms the following day. During the same stay, the fuse blew in her room while using the hotel-provided hair dryer, leaving her without heat for the remainder of the night.\n\nIn my own room, the bathroom mirror was cracked, a nightstand lamp was broken, there was a broken tile under the bathroom sink, and the walls were visibly damaged. Overall, the property felt poorly maintained and, in at least one case, posed a potential health concern.\n\nWhen concerns were raised with the property owner, the response was unwelcoming. We were told that a room with better beds was available for an additional charge, which was disappointing given the overall condition of the hotel.\n\nIn the end, we had to spend a second extremely uncomfortable night at this "motel," as the property manager refused to offer a refund.  Seeing that we had already paid for 7 rooms ahead of time (for 2 nights) through the travel agency, we had no choice but to stay another dreadful night.\n\nI rarely leave negative reviews, but I feel it’s important to be honest so other travelers—especially those expecting comfort or celebrating a special occasion—can make an informed decision. This property did not meet basic expectations for comfort, maintenance, or guest care.	Carla M. Casas	1
