9a3f0540-36df-4d31-b7a0-af1c462b6bd4	cmp1tjo1900agml2i1tbzhz73	I booked a night at Las Qolqas EcoResort in Ollantaytambo to explore the area before starting the Inca Trail, and it delivered exactly what I was hoping for.\n\nBefore arrival, the resort reached out to organise a pickup from town, which made things simple. On arrival I was welcomed with a drink, checked in promptly, and given time to sit and take in the gardens before being shown around the property and escorted to my room. The staff explained all the amenities clearly, and I liked that each tent or suite is themed around the flower that surrounds it.\n\nThe room itself is well suited to a solo traveller or a couple. There is a private deck at the front with sun chairs overlooking the gardens and surrounding mountains. Inside, the bed was comfortable and the tent was well equipped with a heater and fireplace, which made it feel cosy without losing the eco feel. The bathroom was modern and well finished.\n\nThe setting is a standout. The tents are positioned along the river, surrounded by mountains and well maintained gardens, so it feels quiet and secluded without being far from town. I even had a hummingbird in the garden outside my tent, which added to the overall experience.\n\nI opted for the three course dinner on site, which was good and very filling. The portions are generous, so it is worth keeping that in mind.\n\nThe staff were consistently helpful and attentive throughout the stay, and that carried through to departure. They organised a car to get me to the train station earlier than their standard schedule, and because I was leaving before breakfast they prepared a takeaway breakfast pack, which was a practical and appreciated touch.\n\nOverall, this is a well run eco resort in a strong location with a peaceful setting and thoughtful service, and it works very well as a stop before or after the Inca Trail.	Discover with Daroy	5
16a50683-4325-4f21-be23-f1622e04899f	cmp1tjo1900agml2i1tbzhz73	Nice but very overpriced. Know what you are getting - there is a spa, with sauna; but it must be reserved, and only one person/room can reserve by the hour.  And of course, you can't reserve before you arrive! So forget about using it, practically speaking.  Dinner is pretty good, but again, know there is nothing 5 star happening here. Rooms are tents, nice but small - the 8 bed tent has little room to stand up. Well located and really pretty location. But grossly overpriced for what you get. Nowhere near the quality of service or facilities for the price. Very Peruvian in that regard. As an update - hot water is solar powered - so shower before 8 PM or do without.	Sidney Silhan	3
