6ef40c5c-5745-41af-aa52-4935dfe04c9d	cmp1q41i3001xml2i6qssa0se	This place is in a beautiful setting with many archaeological sites to explore right outside the retreat center.  Views of the city are amazing.  The house mama and papa (Bruce and Rose) were friendly and welcoming.\n\ni found the accommodations to be less than I had expected, based on the photos from the website. My room had a “garden” with nothing growing in it except insects, and the only light in this room came from the dirty sky light above the patch of dirt. i had to ask the house papa to re-supply the toilet paper when it was empty.  I had to ask the house papa to empty the toilet paper bins when they became too full to use.  I had to ask the house papa to provide something to dry our hands with in the bathroom when the two communal hand towels disappeared. I had to ask him to please get someone to oil the hinges to the door in the room next to mine.\n\nThe cook was a lovely man, but uninspired. Scrambled eggs with guacamole and bread every single morning. Soup or stew over rice or quinoa every evening.  Perhaps I had been spoiled by the meals i ate on the Inca Trail the week prior, in which our camp chef prepared three meals a day on a three-burner propane stove on the ground, dishing out 6-course lunches and dinners.\n\nThe owner does not live on the property, or even in the country.  I don’t think she would appreciate the condition of the yoga mats, the yoga bolsters, or the yoga blocks.  I was certainly wishing I had brought mine from home rather to use materials that didn’t look like they had been cleaned ever.\n\nI loved my experience here because of the cultural immersion, but the facility left something to be desired.	Shari Vandervelde	3
