6273e43d-5bd1-4917-8165-cb483ec3b674	cmp207bk3000lmlpos6e9yv02	It’s been about seven months since my retreat, where I participated in three ayahuasca ceremonies and one San Pedro ceremony. Each night was different and I don’t think there’s a single takeaway you can package and hand to someone else. The experience gives you something based on what you bring into it and how honestly you’re willing to approach it.\n\nThese are traditional medicines tied to a real culture and history. If someone comes expecting a spectacle or entertainment, they’re going to miss the point. The environment reflects that. This is not a resort and it doesn’t try to be one. You’re removed from distractions so you can actually sit with yourself. You’re comfortable, but comfort isn’t the focus.\n\nErick and Nilda were warm hosts, but more importantly they were clear and transparent about the process. I never felt like anything was being mystified or hidden behind ceremony alone. They acknowledged both the spiritual framing and the psychological reality of what you go through, and the one-on-one conversations the following day helped me process what came up instead of just leaving it as an intense night.\n\nMonths later I’m still unpacking parts of it. For me, it reached places I hadn’t been able to access through conventional therapy alone. That doesn’t mean it replaces anything or works the same for everyone, but the impact has been lasting and practical in my day-to-day life.\n\nI wouldn’t describe it as pleasant or unpleasant — it was meaningful. And that’s really what I went there for.	Andy Filgueira	5
